<worksheet xml:id="activity-09-FTC">
  <title>Reasoning with the FTC</title>
<page>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      You have just bought a new space heater to warm up your dorm room.
      It has a two-stage heating mechanism that includes heating elements and a fan to blow the air around.
    </p>

    <p>
      Let <m>F(t)</m> be the temperature in your room (in degrees Fahrenheit) <m>t</m> hours after midnight on Tuesday, December 2nd.
      While you don't know much about <m>F(t)</m>, you have determined that the <em>rate of change</em> in temperature looks approximately like the graph shown below.
      Let <m>f(t)</m> be the rate at which temperature is changing (in degrees Fahrenheit per hour) <m>t</m> hours after midnight on the same day.
    </p>

    <image width="60%">
      <shortdescription>
        a piecewise linear function showing the rate of change in temperature
      </shortdescription>
      <latex-image>
          \begin{tikzpicture}[yscale=.5]
            		%draw grid
            \draw[ultra thin, color=gray] (-0.1, -2.3) grid (8.3, 2.7);
            %put numbers on axis:
            \foreach \i in {1,...,8} {
              \node[below, fill=white] at (\i,0) {\tiny \i};
            }
            \foreach \i in {-2,...,2} {
              \node[left, fill=white] at (0,\i) {\tiny \i};
            }
            %draw axis:
            \draw[->] (-0.1, 0) -- (8.3, 0) node[below] {$t$};
            \draw[->] (0, -2.3) -- (0, 2.4) node[above left] {$y$};
            %draw graph:
            \draw[line width=2.5pt, line cap=round] (0,2) -- (1,2) -- (2,0) -- (2.01,-2) -- (3,0) -- (4, 2) -- (5,2) -- (7,-2) -- (8,2);
            %label graph:
            \node[below left, fill=white] at (8.3,2.7) {$y = f(t)$};
          \end{tikzpicture}
      </latex-image>
    </image>
  </introduction>

  <exercise workspace=".5in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        What happens at 2am?  What happens to the temperature between 2am and 3am?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace=".5in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        When is the temperature of the room getting colder?  When is it warming up?  How do you know?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>

  <exercise workspace=".5in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        How does the temperature of the room at 3am compare to the temperature at 6am?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
</page>
